[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 1: Parse ICD-10-CM Source Files
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *The pseudocode calls this `parse_icd10_to_graph(source_file_path)`. It reads the CMS order file (a fixed-width text file where each line represents one code) and produces graph nodes and edges. The hierarchy is derived from the code structure itself: E11 is parent of E11.6, which is parent of E11.65.*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m s3_client = boto3.client("s3", region_name=AWS_REGION)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def derive_parent_code(code: str) -> str | None:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Derive the parent code from an ICD-10-CM code by removing the last
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     character of specificity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ICD-10-CM hierarchy is encoded in the code structure:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       E11.65 -> parent is E11.6
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       E11.6  -> parent is E11
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       E11    -> parent is the chapter/block level (handled separately)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     The dot is cosmetic (separates category from subcategory) but the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     hierarchy is purely positional.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Remove the dot for uniform handling. ICD-10 codes are 3-7 chars
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # without the dot (the dot always appears after position 3).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     clean = code.replace(".", "")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if len(clean) <= 3:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # Three-character codes (categories like E11) are children of blocks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # We'll handle block-level parenting separately.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         return None
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Drop the last character to get the parent.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     parent_clean = clean[:-1]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Re-insert the dot if the parent is longer than 3 characters.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if len(parent_clean) > 3:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         return parent_clean[:3] + "." + parent_clean[3:]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     else:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         return parent_clean
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def parse_icd10_order_file(bucket: str, key: str, version: str) -> tuple[list, list]:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Parse the CMS ICD-10-CM order file into graph nodes and edges.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     The order file is a fixed-width text file. Each line contains:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       - Positions 1-5: sequence number
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       - Position 6: blank
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       - Positions 7-13: ICD-10-CM code (no dot, left-justified)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       - Position 14: blank
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       - Position 15: 0 = non-billable header, 1 = billable code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       - Position 16: blank
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       - Positions 17-76: short description (60 chars)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       - Positions 77+: long description
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     CMS publishes this at:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bucket: S3 bucket containing the downloaded CMS file
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         key: S3 key to the order file (e.g., "icd10cm/FY2026/icd10cm_order_2026.txt")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         version: Fiscal year version string (e.g., "FY2026")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Tuple of (nodes_list, edges_list) ready for Neptune bulk load formatting.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Download the order file from S3.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = s3_client.get_object(Bucket=bucket, Key=key)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     content = response["Body"].read().decode("utf-8")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    192[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     nodes = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    193[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     edges = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    194[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    195[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     for line in content.strip().split("\n"):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    196[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         if len(line) < 77:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    197[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             continue  # skip malformed lines
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    198[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    199[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # Parse fixed-width fields.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    200[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # The code field is positions 7-13 (0-indexed: 6:13), no dot included.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    201[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         raw_code = line[6:13].strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    202[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         is_billable = line[14] == "1"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    203[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         short_desc = line[16:76].strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    204[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         long_desc = line[77:].strip() if len(line) > 77 else short_desc
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    205[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    206[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # CMS stores codes without dots. Re-insert the dot after position 3
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    207[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # for codes longer than 3 characters (standard display format).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    208[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         if len(raw_code) > 3:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    209[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             code = raw_code[:3] + "." + raw_code[3:]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    210[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         else:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    211[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             code = raw_code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    212[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    213[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # Determine the chapter from the first character.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    214[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         first_char = code[0].upper()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    215[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         chapter_info = ICD10_CHAPTERS.get(first_char, ("?", "Unknown"))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    216[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    217[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # Create the node for this code.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    218[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         node = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    219[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "id": code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    220[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "label": NODE_LABELS["icd10"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    221[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "description": long_desc,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    222[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "short_desc": short_desc,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    223[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "is_billable": is_billable,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    224[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "chapter": chapter_info[0],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    225[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "version": version,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    226[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    227[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         nodes.append(node)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    228[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    229[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # Derive parent-child edge from code structure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    230[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         parent = derive_parent_code(code)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    231[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         if parent:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    232[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             edge = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    233[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "id": f"{code}_child_of_{parent}",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    234[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "source": code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    235[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "target": parent,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    236[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "label": EDGE_TYPES["is_child_of"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    237[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    238[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             edges.append(edge)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    239[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    240[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    241[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "Parsed %d ICD-10-CM codes, %d parent-child edges from order file",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    242[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         len(nodes), len(edges)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    243[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    244[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return nodes, edges
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    245[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    246[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    247[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    248[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    249[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 2: Parse Cross-Walk Mappings
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    250[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    251[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *The pseudocode calls this `parse_cpt_and_crosswalks(cpt_source, crosswalk_source)`. This step handles the ICD-to-CPT medical necessity mappings that tell you which diagnosis codes justify which procedure codes. The cross-walk data comes from CMS for Medicare (the NCCI edits files).*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    252[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    253[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    254[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def parse_crosswalk_file(bucket: str, key: str) -> list:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    255[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    256[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Parse an ICD-10 to CPT cross-walk file into graph edges.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    257[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    258[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     CMS publishes medical necessity mappings as part of the National Correct
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    259[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Coding Initiative (NCCI). These files map ICD-10 diagnosis codes to CPT
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    260[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     procedure codes that are considered medically necessary given that diagnosis.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    261[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    262[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     The format varies by source. This example assumes a CSV with columns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    263[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     icd_code, cpt_code, effective_date, end_date, payer
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    264[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    265[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     In reality, you'll need separate parsers for:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    266[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - CMS NCCI files (Medicare)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    267[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - LCD/NCD files (local/national coverage determinations)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    268[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - Payer-specific files (commercial plans, each in their own format)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    269[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    270[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    271[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bucket: S3 bucket containing the cross-walk file
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    272[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         key: S3 key to the cross-walk CSV
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    273[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    274[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    275[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         List of edge dictionaries for Neptune bulk load.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    276[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    277[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = s3_client.get_object(Bucket=bucket, Key=key)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    278[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     content = response["Body"].read().decode("utf-8")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    279[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    280[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     edges = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    281[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     reader = csv.DictReader(io.StringIO(content))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    282[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    283[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     for row in reader:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    284[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         icd_code = row["icd_code"].strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    285[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         cpt_code = row["cpt_code"].strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    286[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         payer = row.get("payer", "Medicare").strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    287[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         effective = row.get("effective_date", "").strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    288[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         end_date = row.get("end_date", "").strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    289[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    290[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         edge = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    291[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "id": f"{icd_code}_crosswalk_{cpt_code}_{payer}",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    292[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "source": icd_code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    293[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "target": f"CPT:{cpt_code}",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    294[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "label": EDGE_TYPES["cross_walks_to"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    295[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "payer": payer,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    296[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "effective": effective,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    297[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "end_date": end_date if end_date else "",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    298[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    299[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         edges.append(edge)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    300[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    301[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Parsed %d cross-walk edges from %s", len(edges), key)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    302[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return edges
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    303[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    304[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    305[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def parse_exclusion_annotations(bucket: str, key: str) -> list:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    306[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    307[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Parse ICD-10-CM excludes annotations into graph edges.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    308[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    309[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ICD-10-CM has two types of exclusion relationships:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    310[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - EXCLUDES1: Mutually exclusive. Never code together. The two conditions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    311[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       cannot coexist (e.g., acquired vs. congenital form of same condition).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    312[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - EXCLUDES2: Not included here, but CAN be coded together if both are
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    313[0m:[38;5;10m[49m       documented. Means "this code doesn't cover that concept, look elsewhere."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    314[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    315[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     These annotations are published by CMS alongside the code files.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    316[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Format assumed: CSV with columns: source_code, target_code, type, note
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    317[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    318[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    319[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bucket: S3 bucket containing the annotation file
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    320[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         key: S3 key to the exclusions CSV
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    321[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    322[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    323[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         List of edge dictionaries for Neptune bulk load.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    324[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    325[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = s3_client.get_object(Bucket=bucket, Key=key)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    326[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     content = response["Body"].read().decode("utf-8")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    327[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    328[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     edges = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    329[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     reader = csv.DictReader(io.StringIO(content))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    330[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    331[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     for row in reader:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    332[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         source = row["source_code"].strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    333[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         target = row["target_code"].strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    334[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         exc_type = row["type"].strip().upper()  # "EXCLUDES1" or "EXCLUDES2"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    335[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         note = row.get("note", "").strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    336[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    337[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # Only create edges for recognized exclusion types.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    338[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         if exc_type not in (EDGE_TYPES["excludes1"], EDGE_TYPES["excludes2"]):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    339[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             logger.warning("Unknown exclusion type '%s' for %s -> %s", exc_type, source, target)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    340[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             continue
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    341[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    342[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         edge = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    343[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "id": f"{source}_{exc_type.lower()}_{target}",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    344[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "source": source,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    345[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "target": target,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    346[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "label": exc_type,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    347[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             "note": note,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    348[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    349[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         edges.append(edge)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    350[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    351[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Parsed %d exclusion edges from %s", len(edges), key)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    352[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return edges
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    353[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    354[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    355[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    356[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    357[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 3: Format and Bulk Load into Neptune
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    358[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    359[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *The pseudocode calls this `load_graph_to_neptune(nodes, edges, neptune_endpoint, s3_staging_bucket)`. Neptune's bulk loader expects CSV files in S3 with specific header conventions. Node files need `~id`, `~label`, and property columns. Edge files need `~id`, `~from`, `~to`, `~label`, and property columns.*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    360[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    361[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    362[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def format_nodes_as_neptune_csv(nodes: list) -> str:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    363[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    364[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Transform node dictionaries into Neptune bulk load CSV format.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    365[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    366[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Neptune's CSV loader expects specific column headers:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    367[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - ~id: unique node identifier (required)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    368[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - ~label: node type label (required)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    369[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - property_name:datatype: typed property columns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    370[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    371[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Data types: String (default), Int, Double, Bool, Date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    372[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    373[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     output = io.StringIO()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    374[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     writer = csv.writer(output)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    375[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    376[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Header row with Neptune's required column naming.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    377[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     writer.writerow([
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    378[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "~id",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    379[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "~label",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    380[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "description:String",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    381[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "short_desc:String",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    382[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "is_billable:Bool",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    383[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "chapter:String",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    384[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "version:String",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    385[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    386[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    387[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     for node in nodes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    388[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         writer.writerow([
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    389[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             node["id"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    390[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             node["label"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    391[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             node.get("description", ""),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    392[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             node.get("short_desc", ""),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    393[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             str(node.get("is_billable", False)).lower(),  # Neptune expects "true"/"false"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    394[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             node.get("chapter", ""),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    395[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             node.get("version", ""),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    396[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    397[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    398[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return output.getvalue()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    399[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    400[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    401[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def format_edges_as_neptune_csv(edges: list) -> str:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    402[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    403[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Transform edge dictionaries into Neptune bulk load CSV format.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    404[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    405[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Neptune's edge CSV expects:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    406[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - ~id: unique edge identifier (required)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    407[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - ~from: source node ~id (required)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    408[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - ~to: target node ~id (required)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    409[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - ~label: edge type (required)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    410[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     - property_name:datatype: typed property columns
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    411[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    412[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     output = io.StringIO()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    413[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     writer = csv.writer(output)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    414[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    415[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Header row.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    416[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     writer.writerow([
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    417[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "~id",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    418[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "~from",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    419[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "~to",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    420[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "~label",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    421[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "note:String",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    422[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "payer:String",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    423[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "effective:String",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    424[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "end_date:String",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    425[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     ])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    426[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    427[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     for edge in edges:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    428[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         writer.writerow([
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    429[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             edge["id"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    430[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             edge["source"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    431[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             edge["target"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    432[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             edge["label"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    433[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             edge.get("note", ""),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    434[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             edge.get("payer", ""),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    435[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             edge.get("effective", ""),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    436[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             edge.get("end_date", ""),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    437[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    438[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    439[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return output.getvalue()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    440[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    441[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    442[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def upload_and_bulk_load(nodes: list, edges: list) -> dict:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    443[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    444[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Upload formatted CSVs to S3 and trigger Neptune's bulk loader.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    445[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    446[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     The bulk loader is dramatically faster than inserting nodes one at a time
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    447[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     via openCypher (minutes vs. hours for 70,000+ nodes). It's also idempotent
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    448[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if you use consistent ~id values: reloading the same file updates existing
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    449[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     nodes rather than creating duplicates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    450[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    451[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    452[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Load status response from Neptune.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    453[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    454[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Format as Neptune CSV.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    455[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     node_csv = format_nodes_as_neptune_csv(nodes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    456[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     edge_csv = format_edges_as_neptune_csv(edges)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    457[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    458[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Upload to S3 staging bucket.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    459[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     s3_client.put_object(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    460[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Bucket=STAGING_BUCKET,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    461[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Key="neptune-load/nodes/icd10_nodes.csv",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    462[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Body=node_csv.encode("utf-8"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    463[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    464[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     s3_client.put_object(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    465[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Bucket=STAGING_BUCKET,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    466[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Key="neptune-load/edges/icd10_edges.csv",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    467[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Body=edge_csv.encode("utf-8"),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    468[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    469[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Uploaded %d nodes and %d edges to S3 staging", len(nodes), len(edges))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    470[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    471[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Trigger Neptune bulk load via the loader API.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    472[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # This is a POST to the Neptune loader endpoint (separate from the query endpoint).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    473[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     loader_url = f"https://{NEPTUNE_ENDPOINT}:{NEPTUNE_PORT}/loader"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    474[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    475[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     load_request = {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    476[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "source": f"s3://{STAGING_BUCKET}/neptune-load/",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    477[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "format": "csv",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    478[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "iamRoleArn": NEPTUNE_LOAD_ROLE_ARN,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    479[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "region": AWS_REGION,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    480[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "failOnError": "FALSE",  # log errors but continue loading valid records
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    481[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "parallelism": "HIGH",   # use all available loader threads
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    482[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "updateSingleCardinalityProperties": "TRUE",  # update existing nodes on reload
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    483[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    484[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    485[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = requests.post(loader_url, json=load_request)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    486[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response.raise_for_status()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    487[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     load_result = response.json()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    488[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    489[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     load_id = load_result["payload"]["loadId"]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    490[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Neptune bulk load started: loadId=%s", load_id)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    491[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    492[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return {"load_id": load_id, "status": load_result["status"]}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    493[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    494[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    495[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    496[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    497[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 4: Query the Hierarchy
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    498[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    499[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *The pseudocode calls this `handle_query(request)`. This is where the graph pays off. Queries that would be recursive CTEs in SQL become simple traversal expressions in openCypher. Each function below implements one query pattern from the main recipe.*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    500[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    501[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    502[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def execute_opencypher(query: str, parameters: dict = None) -> list:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    503[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    504[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Execute an openCypher query against Neptune and return the results.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    505[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Neptune's openCypher endpoint accepts POST requests with the query
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     as a form parameter. Parameters are passed separately for safe
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     parameterization (no injection risk).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    511[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         query: openCypher query string with $parameter placeholders
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    512[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         parameters: dict of parameter name -> value
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    513[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    514[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    515[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         List of result rows (each row is a dict of column -> value).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    516[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    517[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     payload = {"query": query}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    518[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if parameters:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    519[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         payload["parameters"] = json.dumps(parameters)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    520[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    521[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response = requests.post(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    522[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         NEPTUNE_OPENCYPHER_URL,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    523[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         data=payload,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    524[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         headers={"Content-Type": "application/x-www-form-urlencoded"},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    525[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    526[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     response.raise_for_status()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    527[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    528[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     result = response.json()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    529[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return result.get("results", [])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    530[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    531[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    532[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def get_children(code: str, depth: int = 99, version: str = "FY2026") -> list:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    533[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    534[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Find all descendant codes under a given code in the hierarchy.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    535[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    536[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     This is the most common query pattern. A population health analyst asks
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    537[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "give me all diabetes codes" and you traverse the subtree under E11.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    538[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A coding tool asks "what are the specific codes under this category?"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    539[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     and you walk one level down.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    540[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    541[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    542[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         code: Starting code (e.g., "E11" for Type 2 diabetes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    543[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         depth: Maximum traversal depth (1 = direct children only, 99 = all)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    544[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         version: Fiscal year version to filter by
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    545[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    546[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    547[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         List of descendant codes with descriptions and depth levels.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    548[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    549[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # openCypher variable-length path pattern: *1..N means 1 to N hops.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    550[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # We traverse IS_CHILD_OF edges in reverse (descendants point UP to parents,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    551[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # so we follow the edge backwards to find children).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    552[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     query = """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    553[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         MATCH path = (start {`~id`: $code})<-[:`IS_CHILD_OF`*1..%d]-(descendant)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    554[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WHERE descendant.version = $version
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    555[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN descendant.`~id` AS code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    556[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                descendant.description AS description,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    557[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                descendant.is_billable AS billable,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    558[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                length(path) AS depth_level
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    559[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ORDER BY descendant.`~id`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    560[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """ % depth  # openCypher in Neptune doesn't support parameterized path lengths
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    561[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    562[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     results = execute_opencypher(query, {"code": code, "version": version})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    563[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("get_children(%s, depth=%d): %d results", code, depth, len(results))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    564[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    565[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    566[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    567[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def get_ancestors(code: str) -> list:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    568[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    569[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Walk up the hierarchy from a code to the chapter level.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    570[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    571[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Useful for reporting rollups: "this patient has E11.65, which rolls up
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    572[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     to E11.6 (complications), which rolls up to E11 (Type 2 DM), which is
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    573[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     in Chapter 4 (Endocrine)."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    574[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    575[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    576[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         code: Starting code (e.g., "E11.65")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    577[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    578[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    579[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         List of ancestor codes ordered from nearest parent to chapter level.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    580[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    581[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     query = """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    582[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         MATCH path = (start {`~id`: $code})-[:`IS_CHILD_OF`*1..10]->(ancestor)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    583[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN ancestor.`~id` AS code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    584[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                ancestor.description AS description,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    585[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                length(path) AS levels_up
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    586[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ORDER BY levels_up
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    587[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    588[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    589[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     results = execute_opencypher(query, {"code": code})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    590[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("get_ancestors(%s): %d levels", code, len(results))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    591[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    592[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    593[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    594[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def get_crosswalks(code: str, target_system: str = "CPT") -> list:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    595[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    596[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Find all codes in another system linked by cross-walk edges.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    597[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    598[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     The critical question for coding and billing: "which CPT procedure codes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    599[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     are justified by this ICD diagnosis code?" Or in reverse: "which diagnoses
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    600[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     support medical necessity for this procedure?"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    601[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    602[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    603[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         code: Source code (e.g., "E11.65")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    604[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         target_system: Target code system label (default "CPT")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    605[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    606[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    607[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         List of cross-walked codes with payer and effective date info.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    608[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    609[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     query = """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    610[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         MATCH (start {`~id`: $code})-[r:`CROSS_WALKS_TO`]->(target)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    611[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WHERE target.`~label` = $target_system
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    612[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN target.`~id` AS code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    613[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                target.description AS description,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    614[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                r.payer AS payer,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    615[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                r.effective AS effective_date
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    616[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ORDER BY target.`~id`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    617[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    618[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    619[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     results = execute_opencypher(query, {"code": code, "target_system": target_system})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    620[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("get_crosswalks(%s -> %s): %d results", code, target_system, len(results))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    621[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    622[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    623[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    624[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def get_exclusions(code: str) -> list:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    625[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    626[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Find codes that cannot be reported together with this one (EXCLUDES1).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    627[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    628[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     EXCLUDES1 means mutually exclusive: these two conditions cannot coexist
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    629[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     in the same patient at the same time. Coding both on the same claim is
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    630[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     always an error. This is different from EXCLUDES2, which means "not
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    631[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     included here, but you CAN code both if both are documented."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    632[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    633[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    634[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         code: Code to check exclusions for (e.g., "E11")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    635[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    636[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    637[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         List of excluded codes with the exclusion note explaining why.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    638[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    639[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     query = """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    640[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         MATCH (start {`~id`: $code})-[r:`EXCLUDES1`]-(excluded)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    641[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN excluded.`~id` AS code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    642[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                excluded.description AS description,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    643[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                r.note AS exclusion_note
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    644[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ORDER BY excluded.`~id`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    645[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    646[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    647[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     results = execute_opencypher(query, {"code": code})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    648[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("get_exclusions(%s): %d exclusions", code, len(results))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    649[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    650[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    651[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    652[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def get_siblings(code: str) -> list:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    653[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    654[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Find codes that share the same parent (sibling codes).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    655[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    656[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Useful for coding assistance: "You picked E11.65, but did you consider
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    657[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     E11.64 or E11.69?" Shows the coder what other options exist at the
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    658[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     same level of specificity.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    659[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    660[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    661[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         code: Code to find siblings for (e.g., "E11.65")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    662[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    663[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    664[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         List of sibling codes (same parent, different code).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    665[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    666[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     query = """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    667[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         MATCH (start {`~id`: $code})-[:`IS_CHILD_OF`]->(parent)<-[:`IS_CHILD_OF`]-(sibling)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    668[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         WHERE sibling.`~id` <> $code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    669[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN sibling.`~id` AS code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    670[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                sibling.description AS description,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    671[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                sibling.is_billable AS billable
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    672[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         ORDER BY sibling.`~id`
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    673[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    674[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    675[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     results = execute_opencypher(query, {"code": code})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    676[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("get_siblings(%s): %d siblings", code, len(results))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    677[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    678[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    679[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    680[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    681[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    682[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Step 5: Handle Version Transitions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    683[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    684[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *The pseudocode calls this `apply_version_update(...)`. When CMS publishes a new ICD-10-CM version each October, the graph needs to incorporate changes without destroying history. New codes get new nodes. Retired codes get SUPERSEDED_BY edges pointing to their replacements.*
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    685[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    686[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    687[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def apply_version_update(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    688[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     bucket: str,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    689[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     new_order_file_key: str,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    690[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     gems_file_key: str,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    691[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     current_version: str,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    692[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     new_version: str,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    693[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ) -> dict:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    694[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    695[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Apply an annual ICD-10-CM version update to the graph.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    696[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    697[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     This function:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    698[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     1. Parses the new version's order file
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    699[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     2. Compares against current graph contents
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    700[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     3. Adds new codes, marks retired codes, updates descriptions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    701[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     4. Creates SUPERSEDED_BY edges using GEMs (General Equivalence Mappings)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    702[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    703[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     The GEMs file maps old codes to new codes when codes are retired or split.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    704[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     CMS publishes GEMs at:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    705[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     https://www.cms.gov/medicare/coding-billing/icd-10-codes/general-equivalence-mappings-gems
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    706[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    707[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    708[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bucket: S3 bucket with the new version files
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    709[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         new_order_file_key: S3 key to the new version's order file
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    710[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         gems_file_key: S3 key to the GEMs mapping file
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    711[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         current_version: Current version string (e.g., "FY2025")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    712[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         new_version: New version string (e.g., "FY2026")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    713[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    714[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    715[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Summary of changes applied.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    716[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    717[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Parse the new version's codes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    718[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     new_nodes, new_edges = parse_icd10_order_file(bucket, new_order_file_key, new_version)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    719[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     new_code_ids = {node["id"] for node in new_nodes}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    720[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    721[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Get current codes from the graph.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    722[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     current_codes_query = """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    723[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         MATCH (n:`ICD10CM` {version: $version})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    724[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         RETURN n.`~id` AS code
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    725[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    726[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     current_results = execute_opencypher(current_codes_query, {"version": current_version})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    727[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     current_code_ids = {r["code"] for r in current_results}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    728[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    729[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Identify changes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    730[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     added_codes = new_code_ids - current_code_ids
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    731[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     retired_codes = current_code_ids - new_code_ids
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    732[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    733[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    734[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "Version update %s -> %s: %d added, %d retired",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    735[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         current_version, new_version, len(added_codes), len(retired_codes)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    736[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    737[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    738[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Parse GEMs file for retired code mappings.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    739[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # GEMs format: source_code, target_code, flags
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    740[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     gems_response = s3_client.get_object(Bucket=bucket, Key=gems_file_key)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    741[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     gems_content = gems_response["Body"].read().decode("utf-8")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    742[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     gems_map = {}  # old_code -> [new_code, ...]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    743[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     for line in gems_content.strip().split("\n"):
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    744[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         parts = line.split(",")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    745[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         if len(parts) >= 2:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    746[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             old_code = parts[0].strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    747[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             new_code = parts[1].strip()
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    748[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             if old_code not in gems_map:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    749[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 gems_map[old_code] = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    750[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             gems_map[old_code].append(new_code)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    751[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    752[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Create SUPERSEDED_BY edges for retired codes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    753[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     superseded_edges = []
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    754[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     for code in retired_codes:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    755[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         replacements = gems_map.get(code.replace(".", ""), [])
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    756[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         for replacement in replacements:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    757[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             # Re-insert dot for display format.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    758[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             if len(replacement) > 3:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    759[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 replacement_formatted = replacement[:3] + "." + replacement[3:]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    760[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             else:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    761[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 replacement_formatted = replacement
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    762[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    763[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             superseded_edges.append({
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    764[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "id": f"{code}_superseded_by_{replacement_formatted}_{new_version}",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    765[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "source": code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    766[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "target": replacement_formatted,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    767[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "label": EDGE_TYPES["superseded_by"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    768[0m:[38;5;10m[49m                 "effective": new_version,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    769[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             })
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    770[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    771[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         # Mark the retired code as inactive.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    772[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         retire_query = """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    773[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             MATCH (n {`~id`: $code})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    774[0m:[38;5;10m[49m             SET n.status = 'RETIRED', n.retired_in = $version
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    775[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    776[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         execute_opencypher(retire_query, {"code": code, "version": new_version})
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    777[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    778[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Bulk load the new nodes and all new edges (hierarchy + superseded).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    779[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     all_new_nodes = [n for n in new_nodes if n["id"] in added_codes]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    780[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     all_new_edges = new_edges + superseded_edges
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    781[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    782[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if all_new_nodes or all_new_edges:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    783[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         upload_and_bulk_load(all_new_nodes, all_new_edges)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    784[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    785[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    786[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "current_version": current_version,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    787[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "new_version": new_version,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    788[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "codes_added": len(added_codes),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    789[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "codes_retired": len(retired_codes),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    790[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "superseded_edges_created": len(superseded_edges),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    791[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    792[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    793[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    794[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    795[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    796[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Putting It All Together
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    797[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    798[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Here's the full pipeline assembled into callable functions. The ETL pipeline runs periodically (annually for ICD, quarterly for CPT). The query functions are what your API Gateway + Lambda setup calls in response to REST requests.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    799[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    800[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```python
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    801[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def run_initial_load():
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    802[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    803[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Run the full initial load pipeline: parse ICD-10-CM codes and
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    804[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     cross-walks, then bulk load into Neptune.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    805[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    806[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     This is what you run once to bootstrap the graph, and then again
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    807[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     each year when CMS publishes the new version.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    808[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    809[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("=== Starting ICD/CPT Hierarchy Initial Load ===")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    810[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    811[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Step 1: Parse ICD-10-CM order file.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    812[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Step 1: Parsing ICD-10-CM order file...")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    813[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     nodes, edges = parse_icd10_order_file(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    814[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bucket=STAGING_BUCKET,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    815[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         key="icd10cm/FY2026/icd10cm_order_2026.txt",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    816[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         version="FY2026",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    817[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    818[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("  Parsed %d nodes, %d edges", len(nodes), len(edges))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    819[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    820[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Step 2: Parse cross-walks and exclusions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    821[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Step 2: Parsing cross-walks and exclusions...")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    822[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     crosswalk_edges = parse_crosswalk_file(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    823[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bucket=STAGING_BUCKET,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    824[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         key="crosswalks/medicare_icd_cpt_crosswalk.csv",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    825[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    826[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     exclusion_edges = parse_exclusion_annotations(
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    827[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         bucket=STAGING_BUCKET,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    828[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         key="icd10cm/FY2026/icd10cm_excludes.csv",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    829[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     )
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    830[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     all_edges = edges + crosswalk_edges + exclusion_edges
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    831[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("  Total edges: %d", len(all_edges))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    832[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    833[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Step 3: Upload and bulk load into Neptune.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    834[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("Step 3: Uploading to S3 and triggering Neptune bulk load...")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    835[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     load_result = upload_and_bulk_load(nodes, all_edges)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    836[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("  Load started: %s", load_result)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    837[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    838[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     logger.info("=== Initial Load Complete ===")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    839[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return load_result
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    840[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    841[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    842[0m:[38;5;10m[49m def handle_api_request(query_type: str, code: str, **kwargs) -> dict:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    843[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    844[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Handle an API request by dispatching to the appropriate query function.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    845[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    846[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     This is what your Lambda query handler calls after parsing the REST request
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    847[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     from API Gateway. In production, you'd add Redis caching here (check cache
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    848[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     first, execute query on miss, store result).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    849[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    850[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Args:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    851[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         query_type: One of "children", "ancestors", "crosswalks", "exclusions", "siblings"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    852[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         code: The ICD-10 or CPT code to query
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    853[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         **kwargs: Additional parameters (depth, version, target_system)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    854[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    855[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     Returns:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    856[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         Structured JSON response.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    857[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     """
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    858[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     depth = kwargs.get("depth", 99)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    859[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     version = kwargs.get("version", "FY2026")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    860[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     target_system = kwargs.get("target_system", "CPT")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    861[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    862[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     if query_type == "children":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    863[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         results = get_children(code, depth=depth, version=version)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    864[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     elif query_type == "ancestors":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    865[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         results = get_ancestors(code)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    866[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     elif query_type == "crosswalks":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    867[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         results = get_crosswalks(code, target_system=target_system)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    868[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     elif query_type == "exclusions":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    869[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         results = get_exclusions(code)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    870[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     elif query_type == "siblings":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    871[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         results = get_siblings(code)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    872[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     else:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    873[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         return {"error": f"Unknown query type: {query_type}"}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    874[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    875[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     return {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    876[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "code": code,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    877[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "query_type": query_type,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    878[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "version": version,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    879[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "results": results,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    880[0m:[38;5;10m[49m         "total_results": len(results),
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    881[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    882[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    883[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    884[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Example usage: run queries against the loaded graph.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    885[0m:[38;5;10m[49m if __name__ == "__main__":
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    886[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Example 1: Get all children of E11 (Type 2 diabetes), depth 2.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    887[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     print("\n--- Children of E11 (depth 2) ---")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    888[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     result = handle_api_request("children", "E11", depth=2)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    889[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     print(json.dumps(result, indent=2))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    890[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    891[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Example 2: Walk up from E11.65 to the chapter level.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    892[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     print("\n--- Ancestors of E11.65 ---")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    893[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     result = handle_api_request("ancestors", "E11.65")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    894[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     print(json.dumps(result, indent=2))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    895[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    896[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Example 3: What CPT codes does E11.65 justify?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    897[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     print("\n--- Cross-walks from E11.65 to CPT ---")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    898[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     result = handle_api_request("crosswalks", "E11.65")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    899[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     print(json.dumps(result, indent=2))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    900[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    901[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Example 4: What codes can't be reported with E11?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    902[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     print("\n--- Exclusions for E11 ---")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    903[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     result = handle_api_request("exclusions", "E11")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    904[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     print(json.dumps(result, indent=2))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    905[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    906[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     # Example 5: What are the sibling codes of E11.65?
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    907[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     print("\n--- Siblings of E11.65 ---")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    908[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     result = handle_api_request("siblings", "E11.65")
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    909[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     print(json.dumps(result, indent=2))
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    910[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    911[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    912[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    913[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    914[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Gap Between This and Production
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    915[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    916[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This example works. Point it at a Neptune cluster with loaded ICD-10-CM data and it will return structured hierarchy traversals. But there's a meaningful distance between "works in a script" and "runs in a coding department handling real claims." Here's where that gap lives:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    917[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    918[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Error handling.** Right now, if Neptune returns an error or the network times out, the whole thing crashes. A production system wraps every Neptune call in try/except blocks with specific handling for connection timeouts (Neptune is in a VPC, network issues happen), query timeouts (broad subtree traversals can be slow), and malformed responses. You want graceful degradation: return a partial result or a clear error message, not a stack trace.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    919[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    920[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Retries and backoff.** Neptune can return throttling errors under sustained query load. The `requests` library doesn't retry by default. A production system uses `urllib3.util.retry.Retry` or a similar mechanism with exponential backoff. For the bulk loader specifically, you need polling logic that checks load status every few seconds until completion.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    921[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    922[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Input validation.** This code trusts its inputs completely. A production system validates that the code parameter matches ICD-10-CM or CPT format before querying, rejects depth values that would cause unreasonably broad traversals (depth=99 on a chapter code returns thousands of results), and sanitizes any user-provided strings before passing them as openCypher parameters (even though parameterized queries prevent injection, defense in depth matters).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    923[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    924[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caching.** The main recipe describes a Redis caching layer. This example skips it entirely. In production, every query function checks Redis first (using a cache key built from code + query_type + depth + version), returns the cached result on hit, and stores the Neptune result on miss. Cache hit rates of 85-95% are typical because the same popular codes get queried repeatedly. Flush the cache on version updates.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    925[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    926[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Connection pooling.** Each `requests.post()` call in this example opens a new HTTPS connection to Neptune. In production, use a `requests.Session()` with connection pooling to reuse TCP connections. Neptune supports persistent connections and the overhead of TLS handshakes on every query adds up at scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    927[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    928[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **IAM least-privilege.** The IAM role for the query Lambda should have exactly `neptune-db:ReadDataViaQuery` (not `neptune-db:*`). The ETL Lambda needs `neptune-db:WriteDataViaQuery` and the loader permissions. The Neptune load role needs only `s3:GetObject` on the specific staging bucket prefix. Separate roles for separate functions.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    929[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    930[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **VPC configuration.** Neptune requires VPC deployment. Your Lambda functions must be in the same VPC with security groups that allow outbound traffic to Neptune's port (8182). Add VPC endpoints for S3 (gateway endpoint, free) and CloudWatch Logs (interface endpoint) so Lambda can reach those services without a NAT gateway.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    931[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    932[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Monitoring.** In production, emit CloudWatch metrics for: query latency (p50, p95, p99), cache hit rate, Neptune connection errors, bulk load duration, and graph size (node/edge counts). Set alarms on query latency spikes (which indicate cache misses after a version update) and on Neptune CPU utilization (which indicates queries that need optimization).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    933[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    934[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **The annual version transition.** The `apply_version_update` function here is simplified. In production, you'd run it in a staging environment first, validate that the new version's hierarchy is correct (spot-check known codes), then promote to production. The GEMs mappings are approximate, not exact. Some retired codes map to multiple replacements (one-to-many splits). Your analytics team needs to understand that historical queries spanning a version boundary may have slight discontinuities.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    935[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    936[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Neptune openCypher limitations.** Neptune's openCypher support is good but not complete. Variable-length path patterns work, but some advanced Cypher features (like APOC procedures from Neo4j) don't exist. The `%d` string formatting for path length in this example is a workaround for Neptune not supporting parameterized path lengths. Test your specific query patterns against Neptune during development, not just against a local Neo4j instance.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    937[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    938[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Testing.** There are no tests here. A production pipeline has unit tests for `derive_parent_code` (with known code/parent pairs), integration tests against a Neptune cluster loaded with a known subset of codes, and validation scripts that verify the loaded graph matches expected node/edge counts. Use the CMS-published code counts as your ground truth.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    939[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    940[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    941[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    942[0m:[38;5;10m[49m *Part of the Healthcare AI/ML Cookbook. See [Recipe 13.3](chapter13.03-icd-cpt-hierarchy-navigation.md) for the full architectural walkthrough, pseudocode, and honest take on where this gets hard.*
